Richard Hugh "Ritchie" Blackmore (born 14 April 1945) is an English guitarist and songwriter.[2][3][4][5] He was one of the founding members of Deep Purple in 1968, playing jam-style hard-rock music which mixed guitar riffs and organ sounds.[6] During his solo career, he established a heavy metal band called Rainbow[7] which fused baroque music influences and elements of hard rock.[8][9] Rainbow steadily moved to catchy pop-style mainstream rock.[7] Later in life, he formed the traditional folk rock project Blackmore's Night transitioning to vocalist-centred sounds. As a member of Deep Purple, Blackmore was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in April 2016.[10]
